    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT300-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">iyaṟkaip puṇarcci puṇarnta talaimakaṉ pirivu accamum vaṉpoṟaiyum kūṟiyatu. </p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Spoken as an encouragement and about the fear of
          separation, by HIM, who had experienced natural union [with her]. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT300">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l> kuvaḷai nāṟuṅ kuvaiyiruṅ kūnta</l>
          <l> lāmpa ṉāṟun tēmpoti tuvarvāyk</l>
          <l> kuṇṭunīrt tāmaraik koṅki ṉaṉṉa</l>
          <l> nuṇpaḵ ṟitti māa yōyē</l>
          <l> nīyē, yañca leṉṟaveṉ collañ calaiyē</l>
          <l> yāṉē, kuṟuṅkā laṉṉaṅ kuvavumaṇaṟ cēkkuṅ</l>
          <l> kaṭalcūḻ maṇṭilam peṟiṉum</l>
          <l> viṭalcū ḻalaṉyā ṉiṉṉuṭai naṭpē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>Dark one with beauty spots fine [and] many</l>
          <l rend="indent4">as the pollen of the red lotus in deep water,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">with a honey-hoarding coral mouth redolent of white waterlilies,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">with massed dark tresses, redolent of blue waterlilies!</l>
          <l>You,</l>
          <l>don't fear my saying “don't be afraid!”<note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> añcalai </term>: Cām./T.V.G. read here too a negative imperative (as <term xml:lang="ta"> añcal </term>), but formally it rather looks like an indicative (for this and similar cases see Agesthialingom p. 77). As for the sentence, it would be nicer with two imperatives: HE begs HER to put trust into his words of reconciliation at the time he has to leave her.    </note>  –</l>
          <l>As for me,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">even if I obtained the sea-girt orb,</l>
          <l rend="indent4">where short-legged geese are resting upon heaped sand <note place="foot"> What is achieved by this line? Is this more than a long, conventional epithet for the sea? </note> ,</l>
          <l>I won't think of <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> kaṭal cūḻ – viṭal cūḻalaṉ </term> is a play on two homonymous roots <term xml:lang="ta"> cūḻ-tal </term>, which unfortunately cannot be reproduced in English. </note> letting go of your <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> niṉṉuṭai naṭpu </term>: "your (unalienable) friendship". </note> friendship.</l>

        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
